05157nam a22005895i 9780822390466DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223904667 a10.1515/97808223904662doi  a(DE-B1597)552937  a(OCoLC)1224278173  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS3556.R78bC55 2008 7aART0160002bisacsh1 aFrueh, Joanna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aClairvoyance (For Those In The Desert) :bPerformance Pieces, 1979-2004 /cJoanna Frueh. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b32 b&w photos, 16 color photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tNota Bene -- tFucking Hot: An Introduction by Jill O'Bryan -- tJOANNA FRUEH'S WRITING -- tThe Concupiscent Critic (1979) -- tBRUMAS (1982) -- tJustifiable Anger (1982-83) -- tDual Conception (1983) -- tSolar Shores (1984) -- tA Few Erotic Faculties (1985-86) -- tClairvoyance (For Those In The Desert) (1985-86) -- tBreathing (1988) -- tVermilion (1988) -- tMouth Piece (1989) -- tAmazing Grace (1990) -- tPythia (1994) -- tDressing Aphrodite (1997) -- tSade, My Sweet, My Truffle; or, Giving a Fuck (1999) -- tThe Aesthetics of Orgasm (2002) -- tVoyaging to Cythera (2003) -- tThe Performance of Pink (2003) -- tAmbrosia (2004) -- tShaking out the Dead -- tJoanna Frueh Performance Chronology (1979-2005) -- tKey Readings from Joanna Frueh's Childhood to the Present0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe performance artist Joanna Frueh has emerged over the past twenty-five years as a wildly original voice in feminist art. Her uninhibited performances are celebrations of beauty, sensuality, eroticism, and pleasure. Clairvoyance (For Those In The Desert), which features eighteen of her essential performance texts, is a celebration of this remarkable artist and her work. Arranged chronologically, from The Concupiscent Critic (1979) through Ambrosia (2004), the pieces reveal Frueh's evolution as an artist and intellectual over the course of her career. Many of these texts have never before been published; others have not been readily available until now. Among the sixteen color photographs in this richly illustrated book are pictures of Frueh performing and images from Joanna in the Desert, a 2006 collaboration between Frueh and the artist and scholar Jill O'Bryan.Frueh's performances are unabashedly autobiographical, as likely to reflect her scholarship as a feminist art historian as her love affairs or childhood memories. For Frueh, eros and self-love are part of a revolutionary feminist strategy; her work exemplifies the physicality and embrace of pleasure that she finds wanting in contemporary feminist theory. Scholarly and rigorous yet playful in tone, her performances are joyful, filled with eroticism, flowers, sexy costumes, and beautiful colors, textures, and scents. Recurring themes include Frueh's passionate attachment to the desert landscape and the idea of transformation: a continual reaching for clarity of thought and feeling.In an afterword as lyrical and breathless as her performance pieces, Frueh explores her identification with the desert and its influence on her art. Clairvoyance (For Those In The Desert) includes a detailed chronology of Frueh's performances.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aFeminismvDrama. 0aPerformance artvTexts. 0aWomenvDrama. 7aART / Individual Artists / General.2bisacsh1 aKochheiser, Frueh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrueh, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDudley, Russell, econtributor.4